text.tspan: The inner workings of a mechanical clock rely
on a gear rotated by a falling weight
A pendulum is commonly used to regulate the
and they have the cool property of swinging
at a fixed period, independent of the initial push
In the "tick" position, the escapement releases
the gear and the gear pushes the pendulum
In order to connect the gear to the pendulum,
we use a device called an escapement
If you configure the length of the pendulum to
swing for one second and you use a gear with
60 cogs, then you get a (minute-only) clock!
In the "tock" position, the escapement catches
the gear at the next cog.
T = Time to swing back and forth
